back Machine]] |accessdate=18 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040528121855/http://www.christianitytoday.com/music/reviews/2004/wire.html |archivedate=May 28, 2004 }}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Cross Rhythms (magazine)|Cross Rhythms]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|8|10|full=U+25A0.svg|empty=Solid white borderedS.svg|rating=square}}<ref name=cr>{{cite web |url=http://www.crossrhythms.co.uk/products/Third_Day/Wire/9867/ |title=Review: Wire - Third Day |last=Cummings |first=Tony |authorlink=Tony Cummings |date=June 9, 2004 |publisher=Cross Rhythms |accessdate=March 28, 2014 }}</ref>\n| rev6 = Jesus Freak Hideout\n| rev6Score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=jfh>{{cite web |url=http://www.jesusfreakhideout.com/cdreviews/Wire.asp |title=Third Day, \"Wire\" Review |last=DiBiase |first=John |date=May 4, 2004 |publisher=Jesus Freak Hideout |accessdate=March 28, 2014 }}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''The Phantom Tollbooth''\n| rev7score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=tptone>{{cite web |url=http://www.tollbooth.org/2004/reviews/wire.html |title=Review of The Phantom Tollbooth (Wray) |last=Wray |first=Burton |date=May 30, 2004 |work=The Phantom Tollbooth |accessdate=March 28, 2014 }}</ref><br />{{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=tpttwo>{{cite web |url=http://www.tollbooth.org/2004/reviews/wire.html |title=Review of The Phantom Tollbooth (Chromey) |last=Chromey |first=Rick |date=June 13, 2004 |work=The Phantom Tollbooth |accessdate=March 28, 2014 }}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n| rev8Score = {{rating|3|4}}<ref name=usa>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2004-05-10-listen-up_x.htm?csp=34|title=Party with Gretchen Wilson, Los Lobos|last=Mansfield|first=Brian|authorlink=Brian Mansfield|date=May 10, 2004|work=USA Today|accessdate=March 28, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Wire''''' is the seventh album by [[Christian rock]] band [[Third Day]]. It breaks from the style of the band's previous albums to return to simple, [[rock and roll]]-driven melodies. To quote [[Allmusic]]'s review of the album, \"Third Day has stripped away the shine and gotten back to the grittiness of being a rock & roll band.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Steven Douglas Losey|date=|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r687808|pure_url=yes}}|title=Wire Review (Allmusic)|accessdate=}}</ref> The album is largely carried by the energetic [[guitar]] riffs that pervade its songs, although the forceful lyrics also contribute significantly.\n\nThe album's songs deal with numerous themes. \"Wire\", the title track, is a song about the pressure to succeed in modern society. \"I Believe\", \"I Got a Feeling\", \"Innocent\", and other tracks deal with [[sin]], faith, and renewal from a [[Christianity|Christian]] perspective. \"Billy Brown\" is a song that explores the readiness of people to follow and even idolize entertainment figures.\n\nIn November 2004, a live version of ''Wire'' was released, called ''[[Live Wire (album)|Live Wire]]'' featuring a [[DVD]] and [[CD]] of songs from their tour of their latest album.\n\nThe album won [[2005 Grammy Awards|2005 Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Gospel Album|Best Rock Gospel Album]].\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track listing\n| headline = Album release\n| all_music     = Third Day\n| title1          = 'Til the Day I Die\n| length1         = 3:25\n| writer1         = Mac Powell\n| title2          = Come on Back to Me\n| length2         = 3:52\n| writer2         = Powell\n| title3          = Wire\n| length3         = 4:31\n| writer3         = Mark Lee\n| title4          = Rockstar\n| length4         = 3:11\n| writer4         = Powell\n| title5          = I Believe\n| length5         = 3:01\n| writer5         = Powell\n| title6          = It's a Shame\n| length6         = 3:56\n| writer6         = Powell\n| title7          = Blind\n| length7         = 4:53\n| writer7         = Powell\n| title8          = I Got a Feeling\n| length8         = 3:36\n| writer8         = Powell\n| title9          = You Are Mine\n| length9         = 3:56\n| writer9         = Powell\n| title10         = Innocent\n| length10        = 4:23\n| writer10        = Lee\n| title11         = Billy Brown\n| length11        = 3:19\n| writer11        = Powell\n| title12         = San Angelo\n| length12        = 5:16\n| writer12        = Powell\n| title13         = I Will Hold My Head High\n| length13        = 4:02\n| writer13        = Lee\n| total_length    = 51:21\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n'''Third Day'''\n* [[Mac Powell]] \u2013 acoustic guitar, lead and backing vocals\n* Brad Avery \u2013 guitar\n* [[Mark David Lee|Mark Lee]] \u2013 guitar\n* Tai Anderson \u2013 bass\n* David Carr \u2013 drums\n\n'''Additional personnel'''\n* Paul Ebersold \u2013 acoustic guitar, [[organ (music)|church organ]], [[Hammond B3 organ]], [[Mellotron]], acoustic piano, programming, string arrangements\n\n==Production==\n* Producer \u2013 Paul Ebersold\n* Executive Producers \u2013 Terry Hemmings, Dave Novik and Dan Raines\n* A&R and consultant \u2013 Robert Beeson\n* A&R production \u2013 Michelle Pearson\n* Engineers \u2013 Don McCollister and Skidd Mills\n* Second engineers \u2013 Mac Attkisson and Scott Hardin\n* Additional engineer \u2013 Billy Bowers\n* Pre-production engineer \u2013 Matt Goldman\n* Mixed by Brendan O'Brien at Southern Tracks, Atlanta, Georgia, assisted by Karl Egsieker\n* Mastered by [[Bob Ludwig]] at Gateway Mastering, Portland, Maine.\n* Art direction \u2013 Scott Hughes and Stephanie McBrayer\n* Cover and packaging \u2013 Bert Sumner\n* Photography \u2013 Marina Chavez\n\n==Awards==\n\nOn 2005, the album won a [[Dove Award]] for Rock/Contemporary Album of the Year at the [[36th GMA Dove Awards]]. The song \"Come on Back to Me\" was also nominated for Rock Recorded Song of the Year.<ref>[http://christianmusic.about.com/od/doves/a/aa36dovenoms.htm 2005 Dove Awards - 36th Annual Dove Awards] on About.com; Jones, Kim</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-al